ates the relationships between the practices and the forms of print, story-telling, drawing and stage performance.It focuses on the creation of new types of cultural work by women and highlights the style of Duval’s drawings relative to both the visual conventions of theatre production and the significance of the visualisation of amateurism and vulgarity.Marie Duval: maverick Victorian cartoonist establishes Duval as a unique but exemplary figure in a transformational period of the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCaricatures and cartoonszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aElectronic books. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMarie Duval.  acomics.  adrawing.  aliterature.  aninteenth century.  aperforming arts.  apublishing.  asynaesthesia.  atheatre.  awood engraving.1 aGrennan, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabin, Roger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSabin, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaite, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWaite, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613355740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526133557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526133557/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles